stein -- tHegel’s Speculative Method and Wittgenstein’s Projection Method -- tA Hegelian Reading of Wittgenstein’s Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus -- tAre There Simple Objects? Hegel’s Discussion of Kant’s Second Antinomy in Relation to Wittgenstein’s Tractatus -- tImage, Reference, and the Level Distinction -- tIdentity in Difference—Wittgenstein’s Hegel -- tPart 5. Wittgensteinian Approaches to Hegel -- tIs the System of Personal Pronouns Somewhat Mysterious? Findlay and Weiss as Critics of Hegel and Wittgenstein -- tParticularity as Paradigm: A Wittgensteinian Reading of Hegel’s Subjective Logic -- t„In der Sprache“ (Wittgenstein) und im „Begriff“ (Hegel) „wird alles ausgetragen“ – Das Sprachspiel des Idealismus -- tSubject Index -- tAuthor Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book brings together for the first time two philosophers from different traditions and different centuries. While Wittgenstein was a focal point of 20th century analytic philosophy, it was Hegel’s philosophy that brought the essential discourses of the 19th century together and developed into the continental tradition in 20th century. This now-outdated conflict took for granted Hegel’s and Wittgenstein’s opposing positions and is being replaced by a continuous progression and differentiation of several authors, schools, and philosophical traditions. The development is already evident in the tendency to identify a progression from a ‘Kantian’ to a ‘Hegelian phase’ of analytical philosophy as well as in the extension of right and left Hegelian approaches by modern and postmodern concepts. Assessing the difference between Wittgenstein and Hegel can outline intersections of contemporary thinking.       aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0